Package adapter

Class CollectionAdapter

  • java.lang.Object
    • adapter.CollectionAdapter
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Collection
    public class CollectionAdapter
extends java.lang.Object
implements Collection

    A collection represents a group of objects, known as its elements. Some collections allow duplicate elements and others do not. Some are ordered and others unordered. Therefore Collecion is a fairly general concept.

    This class implements the Collecion interface, backed by a ListAdapter instance. This Collection admits duplicates but not null elements.

    The iterators returned by this class's iterator() method are not fail-fast.

    This class uses Objects and not generics, for this reason it does not even check that the data present are all of the same type. This awareness lies with the user. The ClassCastException exception is not thrown.

    This class is not thread-safe.

    This class is a member of the adapter package.

      • equals

        public boolean equals​(java.lang.Object o)
        Compares the specified object with this collection for equality.

        The general contract for the Object.equals method states that equals must be symmetric (in other words, a.equals(b) if and only if b.equals(a)). The contracts for List.equals and Set.equals state that lists are only equal to other lists, and sets to other sets. Thus, a custom equals method for a collection class that implements neither the List nor Set interface must return false when this collection is compared to any list or set. (By the same logic, it is not possible to write a class that correctly implements both the Set and List interfaces.)

        Specified by:
        equals in interface Collection
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Parameters:
        o - object to be compared for equality with this collection
        Returns:
        true if the specified object is equal to this collection
        See Also:
        Object.equals(Object), Set.equals(Object), List.equals(Object)

      • toArray

        public java.lang.Object[] toArray()
        Returns an array containing all of the elements in this set. In order from the first that was inserted into the set until the last inserted.

        The returned array will be "safe" in that no references to it are maintained by this set. (In other words, this method must allocate a new array even if this set is backed by an array). The caller is thus free to modify the returned array.

        Specified by:

        Returns:
